variance_musk <- pca_musk$sdev^2 #Variance
var_exp_musk=100 * variance_musk / sum(variance_musk) #  percentage variation explained
In [6]:
plot(cumsum(var_exp_musk), main = "Cumulative Proportion of Variance Explained", xlab = "Principal Component",
              ylab = "Proportion",
              type = "b")

As we can see, the first 3 components cover 52% of the variance and the first 12 components cover the 80% variance of the data. According to the plot above, it is not necessary to use more than 50 variables since the remanining variables does not contribute to the explained variable significantly.

Part C

We can represent each bag with the median of the instances. In this way we don't need to make extra calculations. Also, since choosing median has an advantage of getting rid of the outliers, it might give better results.

Adding noise

In [33]:
r_noise <- runif(dim(r)[1]*dim(r)[2], min(r), 0.1*max(r))
r_noise_matrix=matrix(r_noise,dim(r)[1],dim(r)[2]) 

g_noise <- runif(dim(g)[1]*dim(g)[2], min(g), 0.1*max(g))
g_noise_matrix=matrix(g_noise,dim(g)[1],dim(g)[2]) 

b_noise <- runif(dim(b)[1]*dim(b)[2], min(b), 0.1*max(b))
b_noise_matrix=matrix(b_noise,dim(b)[1],dim(b)[2]) 

r_new <- r + r_noise_matrix 
g_new <- g + g_noise_matrix 
b_new <- b + b_noise_matrix

In [44]:
variance <- pca_image$sdev^2 #Variance
var_exp=100 * variance / sum(variance) #  percentage variation explained
In [45]:
plot(cumsum(var_exp), main = "Cumulative Proportion of Variance Explained", xlab = "Principal Component",
              ylab = "Proportion",
              type = "b")

As we can see, the first 3 components cover 50% of the variance and the first 5 components cover the 60% variance of the data. According to the plot above, it is not necessary to use more than 100 variables since the remanining variables does not contribute to the explained variable significantly.
